00:00:20.689 --> 00:00:21.480
PROFESSOR: Alright.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:27.790
So what we are doing
is covering 8.334,

00:00:27.790 --> 00:00:30.225
which is statistical physics.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:41.160
ANd let me remind you that
basically statistical physics

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:52.630
is a bridge from microscopic
to macroscopic perspectives.

00:00:52.630 --> 00:00:58.330
And I'm going to emphasize a
lot on changing perspectives.

00:00:58.330 --> 00:01:03.210
So at the level
of the micro, you

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:08.760
have the microstate that
is characterized, maybe,

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:14.070
by a collection of momenta
and coordinates of particles,

00:01:14.070 --> 00:01:17.390
such as particles
of gas in this room.

00:01:17.390 --> 00:01:20.830
Maybe those
particles have spins.

00:01:20.830 --> 00:01:24.870
If you are absorbing
things on a surface,

00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:27.840
you may have variables that
denote the occupation--

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:31.820
whether a particle or
site is occupied or not.

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:36.600
And when you're looking
at the microscopic world,

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:39.340
typically you are
interested in how

00:01:39.340 --> 00:01:41.800
things change as a
function of time.

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:45.170
You have a kind of
dynamics that is governed

00:01:45.170 --> 00:01:48.340
by some kind of a
[INAUDIBLE] which

00:01:48.340 --> 00:01:53.110
is dependent on the microstate
that you are looking at,

00:01:53.110 --> 00:01:57.071
and tells you about the
evolution of the microstate.

00:01:57.071 --> 00:02:00.460
At the other extreme,
you look at the world

00:02:00.460 --> 00:02:05.780
around you and the macro world.

00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:09.919
You're dealing with
things that are described

00:02:09.919 --> 00:02:11.910
by completely different things.

00:02:11.910 --> 00:02:14.320
For example, if you're
thinking about the gas,

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:15.340
you have the pressure.

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:17.310
You have the volume.

00:02:17.310 --> 00:02:20.450
So somehow, the
coordinates managed

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:26.900
to define and macrostate,
which is characterized

00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:29.860
by a few parameters
in equilibrium.

00:02:29.860 --> 00:02:33.680
If you have something like
a collection of spins,

00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:37.030
maybe you will have
a magnetization.

00:02:37.030 --> 00:02:38.870
And again, another
important thing

00:02:38.870 --> 00:02:41.280
that characterizes
the equilibrium we

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:44.140
describe as temperature.

00:02:44.140 --> 00:02:45.980
And when you're
looking at things

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:50.870
from the perspective of
macro systems in equilibrium,

00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:56.170
then you have the
laws of thermodynamics

00:02:56.170 --> 00:03:01.810
that govern constraints that
are placed on these variables.

00:03:01.810 --> 00:03:05.290
So totally different
perspectives.

00:03:05.290 --> 00:03:10.580
And what we have is that we
need to build a bridge from one

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:13.710
to the other and this
bridge is provided

00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:16.490
by statistical mechanics.

00:03:16.490 --> 00:03:21.650
And the way that we described
it in the previous course

00:03:21.650 --> 00:03:25.710
is that to what you need is
a probabilistic prescription.

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:28.950
So rather than following
the time evolution

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:31.180
of all of these
degrees of freedom,

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:33.280
you'll have a
probability assigned

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:36.700
to the different
microstates that

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:39.640
are dependent on
the macro state.

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:41.470
And for example,
if you are dealing

00:03:41.470 --> 00:03:44.240
in the canonical
ensemble, then you

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:46.660
know you're at the
particular temperature

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:51.040
this form has E to the
minus beta, this Hamiltonian

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:54.930
that we you have here
governing the dynamics.

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:57.320
Beta was one over KT.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:01.070
So I could write
it in this fashion.

00:04:01.070 --> 00:04:05.880
And the thing that
enabled us to make

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:11.030
a connection between this
deterministic perspective

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:15.780
and this equilibrium description
wire probabilities abilities

00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:21.910
was relying on the limit
where the number of degrees

00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:25.070
of freedom was very large.

00:04:25.070 --> 00:04:28.350
And this very large number
of degrees of freedom

00:04:28.350 --> 00:04:32.840
enabled us to, although we had
something that was probably

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:36.810
realistic, to really make very
precise statements about what

00:04:36.810 --> 00:04:39.080
was happening.

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:45.036
Now, when we were doing
this program in 8-333,

00:04:45.036 --> 00:04:50.490
we looked at very simple systems
that were essentially non

00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:54.730
interacting, like the ideal gas.

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:58.470
Or we put a little bit
of weak perturbation

00:04:58.470 --> 00:05:04.430
and by some manipulations,
we got things like liquids.

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:07.690
But the important thing is
that where is this program

00:05:07.690 --> 00:05:12.380
we could carry out precisely
when we had no interactions.

00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:18.320
In the presence
of interactions we

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:22.350
encountered, even in our
simplified perspective,

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:23.140
new things.

00:05:23.140 --> 00:05:25.910
We went from the gas
state to a liquid state.

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:28.430
We didn't discuss
it, but we certainly

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:30.850
said a few things about solids.

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:36.700
And clearly there are much
more interesting things

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:39.430
that can happen when
you have interactions.

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:43.060
You could have other phases of
matter that we didn't discuss,

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:50.000
such as liquid crystals,
superconductors,

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.050
and many, many other things.

00:05:55.050 --> 00:06:02.570
So the key idea is that you
can solve things that are not

00:06:02.570 --> 00:06:04.950
interacting going
their own ways,

00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:08.260
but when you put
interactions, you

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:10.990
get interesting
collective behaviors.

00:06:16.900 --> 00:06:22.780
And what we want to do
in 8-334, as opposed

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:26.990
to just building the
machinery in 8-333,

00:06:26.990 --> 00:06:30.150
is to think about all
of the different types

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:33.060
of collective behavior
that are possible

00:06:33.060 --> 00:06:39.020
and how to describe them in
the realm of classical systems.

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:42.610
So we won't go much into the
realm of quantum systems, which

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:46.420
is also quite interesting as far
as its own collective behaviors

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:48.310
is concerned.

00:06:48.310 --> 00:06:51.390
So that's the program.

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:54.630
Now, what I would
like to do is to go

00:06:54.630 --> 00:06:58.800
to the description of the
organization of the class,

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:03.770
and hopefully this web
page will come back online.

00:07:13.930 --> 00:07:20.700
So repeating what I was
saying before, the idea is

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:24.310
that interactions
give rise to a variety

00:07:24.310 --> 00:07:27.950
of interesting
collective behaviors,

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:32.440
starting from pretty much
simple degrees of freedom

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:35.130
such as atoms and molecules
and adding a little bit

00:07:35.130 --> 00:07:37.960
of interactions and
complexity to them,

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:43.570
you could get a variety of, for
example, liquid crystal phases.

00:07:43.570 --> 00:07:49.150
But one of things to think about
is that you think about all

00:07:49.150 --> 00:07:52.260
of the different atoms
and molecules that you

00:07:52.260 --> 00:07:55.670
can put together, and the
different interactions that you

00:07:55.670 --> 00:07:59.270
could put among them-- you
could even imagine things

00:07:59.270 --> 00:08:02.970
that you construct in the lab
that didn't exist in nature--

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:08.570
and you put them together,
but the types of new behavior

00:08:08.570 --> 00:08:11.390
that you encounter
is not that much.

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:15.380
At some level, you learn about
the three phases of matter,

00:08:15.380 --> 00:08:20.150
gas, liquids, solids, of course,
as I said, there are many more,

00:08:20.150 --> 00:08:22.540
but there are not
hundreds of them.

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:24.270
There are just a few.

00:08:24.270 --> 00:08:28.790
So the question is why, given
the complexity of interactions

00:08:28.790 --> 00:08:31.530
that you can have at
the microscopic scale,

00:08:31.530 --> 00:08:33.919
you put things
together, and you really

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:37.370
don't get that many
variety of things

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:39.330
at the macroscopic level.

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:44.190
And the answer has to do with
mathematical consistency,

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:47.370
and has at its heart
something that you already

00:08:47.370 --> 00:08:51.570
saw in 8-333, which is
the central limit theorem.

00:08:51.570 --> 00:08:56.880
You take many random
variables of whatever ilk

00:08:56.880 --> 00:08:59.820
and you add them
together, and the sum

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:03.010
has a nice simple
Gaussian distribution.

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:08.830
So somehow mathematics forces
things to become simplified

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:11.740
when you put many
of them together.

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:13.680
So the same thing
is happening when

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:16.950
you put lots of interacting
pieces together.

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:20.290
New collective behaviors
emerge, but because

00:09:20.290 --> 00:09:22.580
of the simplification,
in the same sense

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:25.390
the type of simplification that
we see with the central limit

00:09:25.390 --> 00:09:28.900
theorem, there aren't that
many consistent mathematical

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:31.750
descriptions that can emerge.

00:09:31.750 --> 00:09:36.480
Of course, there
are nice new ones,

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:40.050
and the question is
how to describe them.

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:46.500
So this issue of what
are possible consistent

00:09:46.500 --> 00:09:49.800
mathematical forms
is what we will

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:53.190
address through constructing
these statistical field

00:09:53.190 --> 00:09:54.120
theories.

00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:57.830
So one of the
important things that I

00:09:57.830 --> 00:10:05.090
will try to impose upon you
is to change your perspective.

00:10:05.090 --> 00:10:08.640
In the same way that there is
a big change of perspective

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:12.970
thinking about the microscopic
and macroscopic board,

00:10:12.970 --> 00:10:16.770
there is also a change
of perspective involved

00:10:16.770 --> 00:10:22.240
in the idea of starting from
interacting degrees of freedom,

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:24.730
and changing perspective
and constructing

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:26.770
a statistical future.

00:10:26.770 --> 00:10:29.550
And I'll give you one
example of that today

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:32.370
that you're hopefully
all familiar with,

00:10:32.370 --> 00:10:36.710
but it shows very much how this
change of perspective works,

00:10:36.710 --> 00:10:38.720
and that's the
kind of metallurgy

00:10:38.720 --> 00:10:41.800
that we will apply
in this course.

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:47.780
Basically the syllabus
is as follows.

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:56.650
So initially I will try
to emphasize to you how,

00:10:56.650 --> 00:11:00.360
by looking at things,
by averaging over

00:11:00.360 --> 00:11:06.660
many degrees of freedom, at long
lens scales and time scales,

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:11.660
you get simplified statistical
field theory descriptions.

00:11:11.660 --> 00:11:14.070
The simplest one of
these that appears

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:18.120
in many different contexts
is this Landau-Ginzburg model

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:22.820
that will occupy us for
quite a few lectures.

00:11:22.820 --> 00:11:25.955
Now once you construct
a description of one

00:11:25.955 --> 00:11:27.680
of these statistical
field theories,

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:30.510
the question is how
do you solve it.

00:11:30.510 --> 00:11:32.850
And there are a
number of approaches

00:11:32.850 --> 00:11:37.450
that we will follow such as
mean field theory, et cetera.

00:11:37.450 --> 00:11:40.830
And what we'll find is
that those descriptions

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:43.430
fail in certain dimensions.

00:11:43.430 --> 00:11:46.070
And then to do
better than that, you

00:11:46.070 --> 00:11:50.160
have to rely on things such
as perturbation theory.

00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:52.490
So this is kind of
perturbation theory

00:11:52.490 --> 00:11:55.350
that builds upon the types
of perturbation theory

00:11:55.350 --> 00:11:58.130
that we did in the
previous semester, what

00:11:58.130 --> 00:12:00.860
is closer to the kind
of perturbation theory

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:05.330
that you would be doing
in quantum field theories.

00:12:05.330 --> 00:12:07.885
Alongside these
continuum theories,

00:12:07.885 --> 00:12:13.480
I will also develop some lattice
models, that in certain limits,

00:12:13.480 --> 00:12:19.040
are simpler and admit
either numerical approaches

00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:22.380
or exact solutions.

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:26.940
The key idea that we
will try to learn about

00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:31.110
is that of Kadanoff's
perspective of renormalization

00:12:31.110 --> 00:12:35.480
group and how you
can, in some sense,

00:12:35.480 --> 00:12:38.600
change your perspective
continuously

00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:42.160
by looking at how a
system would look over

00:12:42.160 --> 00:12:44.730
larger and larger
landscape, and how

00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:48.150
the mathematical description
that you have for the system

00:12:48.150 --> 00:12:51.250
changes as a function of
the scale of observation,

00:12:51.250 --> 00:12:57.250
and hopefully becomes simple
at sufficiently large scales.

00:12:57.250 --> 00:13:03.060
So we will conclude by looking
at a variety of applications

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:05.260
of the methodologies
that we have developed.

00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:08.640
For example, in the context
of two dimensional films,

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:15.180
and potentially if we have
time, a number of other systems.

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:20.930
The first thing that I'm going--
the rest of the lecture today

00:13:20.930 --> 00:13:24.900
has essentially nothing in
common with the material

00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:29.000
that we will start to cover
as of the second lecture.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.380
But it illustrates this
change in perspective

00:13:32.380 --> 00:13:35.880
that is essential to
the way of thinking

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:38.860
about the material
in this course.

00:13:38.860 --> 00:13:45.490
And the context that I will use
to introduce this perspective

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:47.040
is phonons and elasticity.

00:13:55.810 --> 00:14:00.680
So you look around you,
there's a whole bunch

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:03.360
of different solids.

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:07.090
There's metals, there's
wood, et cetera.

00:14:07.090 --> 00:14:09.380
And for each one
of them, you can

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:13.330
ask things about their
thermodynamic properties, heat

00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:17.230
content, for example,
heat capacity.

00:14:17.230 --> 00:14:21.560
They are constructed of various
very different materials.

00:14:21.560 --> 00:14:24.900
And so let's try
to think, if you're

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:29.130
going to start
from this left side

00:14:29.130 --> 00:14:31.470
from the microscopic
perspective,

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:35.000
how we would approach
the problem of the heat

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.200
content of these solids.

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:47.570
So you would say that solids,
if I were to go to 0 temperature

00:14:47.570 --> 00:14:52.073
before I put any heat into them,
they would be perfect crystals.

00:14:56.060 --> 00:14:57.570
What does that mean?

00:14:57.570 --> 00:15:06.000
It means that if I look at
the positions of these atoms

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.300
or particles that are making
up the crystal-- I guess

00:15:09.300 --> 00:15:15.180
I have to be more specific since
a metal is composed of nuclei

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:16.940
and electrons--
let's imagine that we

00:15:16.940 --> 00:15:19.860
look at the positions
of the ions.

00:15:19.860 --> 00:15:23.320
Then in the perfect
position they

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:27.450
will form a lattice where I
will pick three integers, L M

00:15:27.450 --> 00:15:35.110
N and three unit
vectors, and I can

00:15:35.110 --> 00:15:40.960
list the positions of all of
these ions in the crystal.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:47.180
So this combination
L M N that indicates

00:15:47.180 --> 00:15:52.620
the location of some particular
ion in the perfect solid

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:56.820
that's indicated by,
let's say, the vector r.

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:03.580
So this is the position that I
would have ideally for the ion

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:07.530
at zero temperature
that is labelled by r.

00:16:07.530 --> 00:16:10.460
Now, of course when we go
to finite temperatures,

00:16:10.460 --> 00:16:16.815
the particles, rather than
forming this nice lattice,

00:16:16.815 --> 00:16:20.910
let's imagine a square
lattice in two dimension,

00:16:20.910 --> 00:16:24.040
starts to move around.

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:29.980
And they're no longer going
to be perfect positions.

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:37.800
And these distortions we can
indicate by some vector u.

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:43.980
So when we have perfect
crystals across deformations,

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:48.930
this Q star changes
to a new position,

00:16:48.930 --> 00:16:57.110
Q of r, which is it's ideal
position plus a distortion

00:16:57.110 --> 00:17:02.350
field u, at each location.

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:04.260
OK?

00:17:04.260 --> 00:17:07.940
Now associated with these
change of positions,

00:17:07.940 --> 00:17:12.619
you have moved away from the
lowest energy configuration.

00:17:12.619 --> 00:17:15.030
You have put energy
in the system.

00:17:15.030 --> 00:17:19.680
And you would say that
the energy of the system

00:17:19.680 --> 00:17:22.470
is going to be composed
of the following parts.

00:17:22.470 --> 00:17:26.240
There's always going to be
some kind of a kinetic energy.

00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:32.650
That's sum over r p
r squared over 2 m.

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:36.780
Let's imagine particles
all have the same mass m.

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:43.760
And then the reason
that these particles

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:46.830
form this perfect
crystal was presumably

00:17:46.830 --> 00:17:49.620
because of the overlap
of electronic wave

00:17:49.620 --> 00:17:50.950
functions, et cetera.

00:17:50.950 --> 00:17:54.980
Eventually, if you're
looking at these coordinates,

00:17:54.980 --> 00:17:58.070
there's some kind of
a many body potential

00:17:58.070 --> 00:18:01.546
as a function of the positions
of all of these particles.

00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:13.970
Now, what we are doing
is we are looking

00:18:13.970 --> 00:18:17.970
at distortions that are small.

00:18:17.970 --> 00:18:19.690
So let's imagine
that you haven't

00:18:19.690 --> 00:18:24.180
gone to such high temperatures
where this crystal completely

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:27.300
melts and disappears and
gives us something else.

00:18:27.300 --> 00:18:32.490
But we have small
changes from what

00:18:32.490 --> 00:18:35.740
we had at zero temperature.

