00:27:03.350 --> 00:27:07.610
And presumably as
you span K, you

00:27:07.610 --> 00:27:12.400
will have a whole
bunch of lines that

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:16.260
will correspond to the
variations of these frequencies

00:27:16.260 --> 00:27:18.910
as a function of K.

00:27:18.910 --> 00:27:21.030
Why is that useful?

00:27:21.030 --> 00:27:23.180
Well, the reason
that it's useful

00:27:23.180 --> 00:27:26.840
is that as you go
to high temperature,

00:27:26.840 --> 00:27:31.770
you put the energies into these
normal modes and frequencies.

00:27:31.770 --> 00:27:35.380
That's why this whole
lattice is vibrating.

00:27:35.380 --> 00:27:38.150
And the amount of
energy that you

00:27:38.150 --> 00:27:45.110
have put at temperature
T on top of this V0

00:27:45.110 --> 00:27:48.470
that you had at
zero temperature,

00:27:48.470 --> 00:27:51.290
up to constants
of proportionality

00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:54.520
that I don't want
to bother with is

00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:59.410
a sum over all of these normal
modes that are characterized

00:27:59.410 --> 00:28:06.480
by K and alpha, the polarization
and the wave vector.

00:28:06.480 --> 00:28:08.370
And the amount of
energy, then, that you

00:28:08.370 --> 00:28:14.030
would put in one harmonic
oscillator of frequency omega.

00:28:14.030 --> 00:28:16.010
And that is something
that's we know

00:28:16.010 --> 00:28:23.235
to be h bar omega alpha of
K, divided by e to the beta h

00:28:23.235 --> 00:28:26.960
bar omega alpha of K minus 1.

00:28:30.970 --> 00:28:33.650
So the temperature
dependence then

00:28:33.650 --> 00:28:37.480
appears in this factor
of beta over here.

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:40.550
So the energy
content went there,

00:28:40.550 --> 00:28:43.350
and if you want to,
for example, ultimately

00:28:43.350 --> 00:28:46.640
calculate heat capacity,
I have to calculate

00:28:46.640 --> 00:28:49.020
this whole quantity as a
function of temperature.

00:28:49.020 --> 00:28:52.150
And then take the derivative.

00:28:52.150 --> 00:28:57.380
So it seems like, OK, I have to
do this for every single solid,

00:28:57.380 --> 00:29:01.970
whether it's copper,
aluminium, wood, or whatever.

00:29:01.970 --> 00:29:05.630
I have to figure out what
these frequencies are,

00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:08.320
what's the energy content
in each frequency.

00:29:08.320 --> 00:29:13.415
And it seems like a complicated
engineering problem,

00:29:13.415 --> 00:29:14.900
if you like.

00:29:14.900 --> 00:29:19.150
Is that it about
this that transcends

00:29:19.150 --> 00:29:24.990
having to look at all of these
details and come to this?

00:29:24.990 --> 00:29:27.760
And of course, you know
the answer already,

00:29:27.760 --> 00:29:31.920
which is that if I go to
sufficiently low temperature,

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:37.930
I know that the heat capacity
due to phonons for all solids

00:29:37.930 --> 00:29:40.540
goes like t cubed.

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:44.100
So somehow, all of
this complexity,

00:29:44.100 --> 00:29:48.010
if I go to low enough
temperature, disappears.

00:29:48.010 --> 00:29:53.610
And some universal law emerges
that is completely independent

00:29:53.610 --> 00:29:56.390
of all of these
details-- microscopics,

00:29:56.390 --> 00:29:58.890
interactions, et cetera.

00:29:58.890 --> 00:30:03.400
So our task-- this is the
change of perspective--

00:30:03.400 --> 00:30:08.660
is to find a way to
circumvent all of these things

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:13.110
and get immediately to the heart
of the matter, the part that

00:30:13.110 --> 00:30:16.510
is independent of the details.

00:30:16.510 --> 00:30:18.320
Not that the details
are irrelevant.

00:30:18.320 --> 00:30:20.900
Because after all, if you
want to give some material

00:30:20.900 --> 00:30:24.030
that functions at some
particular set of temperatures,

00:30:24.030 --> 00:30:28.320
you would need to know much
more than this t cubed law

00:30:28.320 --> 00:30:30.260
that I'm telling you about.

00:30:30.260 --> 00:30:33.460
But maybe from the
perspective of what

00:30:33.460 --> 00:30:37.610
I was saying before-- how
many independent forms there

00:30:37.610 --> 00:30:41.470
are, in the same sense that
adding up random variables

00:30:41.470 --> 00:30:42.896
always gives you a Gaussian.

00:30:42.896 --> 00:30:45.270
Of course, you don't know
where the mean and the variance

00:30:45.270 --> 00:30:48.590
of the Gaussian is, but you are
sure that it's a Gaussian form.

00:30:48.590 --> 00:30:52.420
So similarly, there is some
universality in the knowledge

00:30:52.420 --> 00:30:55.130
that, no matter how
complicated the material is,

00:30:55.130 --> 00:30:58.230
its low temperature heat
capacity is t cubed.

00:30:58.230 --> 00:31:04.750
Can we get that by an approach
