00:56:40.690 --> 00:56:42.140
So that's a symmetry.

00:56:42.140 --> 00:56:45.220
Essentially, it's this
translation of symmetry

00:56:45.220 --> 00:56:49.200
that I was saying right
here at the beginning,

00:56:49.200 --> 00:56:52.540
that this only depends on
the separation of two points.

00:56:52.540 --> 00:56:54.500
It's the same thing.

00:56:54.500 --> 00:56:59.740
But what that means is that
when you write your density

00:56:59.740 --> 00:57:04.540
function, then the density
cannot depend on U of x.

00:57:04.540 --> 00:57:05.950
Because that would violate this.

00:57:05.950 --> 00:57:08.870
So you can only be
start with things

00:57:08.870 --> 00:57:15.162
that depend on the U of V
IBX this second, et cetera.

00:57:15.162 --> 00:57:16.220
So this is 1.

00:57:16.220 --> 00:57:18.210
This is 2.

00:57:18.210 --> 00:57:20.800
Another thing is what
I call stability.

00:57:24.680 --> 00:57:30.790
You are looking at distortions
around a state that corresponds

00:57:30.790 --> 00:57:36.130
to being a stable
configuration of your system.

00:57:36.130 --> 00:57:40.750
What that means is that you
cannot have any pairs in this

00:57:40.750 --> 00:57:42.810
expansion that are linear.

00:57:42.810 --> 00:57:45.760
So again, this was
implicit in everything

00:57:45.760 --> 00:57:47.620
that we did over here.

00:57:47.620 --> 00:57:49.370
We went to second order.

00:57:49.370 --> 00:57:52.920
But there's third order, et
cetera, are not ruled out.

00:57:52.920 --> 00:57:54.610
It is more than that.

00:57:54.610 --> 00:57:58.590
Because you require the second
order terms to have the right

00:57:58.590 --> 00:58:01.090
sign, so that your
system corresponds

00:58:01.090 --> 00:58:04.116
to being at the bottom
of a quadratic potential

00:58:04.116 --> 00:58:06.200
rather than the top of it.

00:58:06.200 --> 00:58:10.040
So there is a bit more than
the absence of linear terms.

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:13.490
So given that, you would
say that your potential

00:58:13.490 --> 00:58:18.480
for this system as a function
now of this distortion

00:58:18.480 --> 00:58:23.780
is something like
an integral over x.

00:58:23.780 --> 00:58:26.550
And the first thing that is
consistent with everything

00:58:26.550 --> 00:58:29.960
we have written so
far is that if we

00:58:29.960 --> 00:58:34.740
be proportional to
du by dx squared.

00:58:34.740 --> 00:58:36.860
So there's a coefficient
that I can put here.

00:58:36.860 --> 00:58:39.790
Let's call it k over 2.

00:58:39.790 --> 00:58:41.590
It cannot depend on you.

00:58:41.590 --> 00:58:44.530
It has to be quadratic
function of derivative.

00:58:44.530 --> 00:58:46.520
That's the first thing
I can write down.

00:58:46.520 --> 00:58:50.380
I can certainly write
down something like d2u

00:58:50.380 --> 00:58:53.820
by dx to the fourth power.

00:58:53.820 --> 00:58:58.480
And if I consider higher
order terms, why not something

00:58:58.480 --> 00:59:04.039
like the second
derivative squared,

00:59:04.039 --> 00:59:10.830
first derivative squared, a
whole bunch of other things.

00:59:10.830 --> 00:59:15.090
So again, there's still
many, many, many terms

00:59:15.090 --> 00:59:16.570
that I can't write down.

00:59:16.570 --> 00:59:17.825
Yes?

00:59:17.825 --> 00:59:20.300
Is that second
term supposed to be

00:59:20.300 --> 00:59:22.775
a second derivative
to the fourth power?

00:59:22.775 --> 00:59:24.755
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:59:24.755 --> 00:59:27.740
Thank you.

00:59:27.740 --> 00:59:33.460
So that when I fully
transform this,

00:59:33.460 --> 00:59:40.450
the quadratic part becomes
sum over k, k over 2.

00:59:40.450 --> 00:59:44.340
This fully transformed,
becomes k squared.

00:59:44.340 --> 00:59:45.840
This fully transformed,
as you said,

00:59:45.840 --> 00:59:49.560
is second derivative squared.

00:59:49.560 --> 00:59:51.490
So it becomes k to the fourth.

00:59:51.490 --> 00:59:54.416
I have a whole bunch of terms.

00:59:54.416 --> 00:59:58.912
And then I have U of k squared.

00:59:58.912 --> 01:00:01.190
And then I will have higher
order terms from Fourier

01:00:01.190 --> 01:00:02.550
fully transform of this.

01:00:02.550 --> 01:00:03.100
Yes?

01:00:03.100 --> 01:00:05.820
AUDIENCE: Does this actually
forbid odd derivatives?

01:00:05.820 --> 01:00:08.840
Are you saying the third
derivative and stuff don't--

01:00:08.840 --> 01:00:11.790
PROFESSOR: I didn't go into
