01:02:10.130 --> 01:02:10.370
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:02:10.370 --> 01:02:12.161
AUDIENCE: It seems like
displacing in space

01:02:12.161 --> 01:02:13.695
would mean adding up to x.

01:02:13.695 --> 01:02:14.771
PROFESSOR: No.

01:02:14.771 --> 01:02:15.270
No.

01:02:15.270 --> 01:02:17.930
It is this displacement.

01:02:17.930 --> 01:02:21.100
I take U1, U2, U3, U4.

01:02:21.100 --> 01:02:23.760
U1 becomes U1 plus .3.

01:02:23.760 --> 01:02:26.162
U2 becomes U2 plus .3.

01:02:26.162 --> 01:02:27.272
Everybody moves in step.

01:02:27.272 --> 01:02:29.230
AUDIENCE: So the conclusion
is the coefficients

01:02:29.230 --> 01:02:31.280
don't depend on x?

01:02:31.280 --> 01:02:36.030
PROFESSOR: If you have a
system that is uniform--

01:02:36.030 --> 01:02:39.780
so this statement here
actually depends on uniformity.

01:02:39.780 --> 01:02:42.265
This is an additional
thing, uniform.

01:02:42.265 --> 01:02:45.150
So one part of the
material is the same.

01:02:45.150 --> 01:02:47.990
Now, you have
non-uniform systems.

01:02:47.990 --> 01:02:50.730
So you take your crystal
and you bombard it

01:02:50.730 --> 01:02:52.510
with neutrons or whatever.

01:02:52.510 --> 01:02:55.300
Then you have defects
all over the place.

01:02:55.300 --> 01:02:57.220
Then one location
will be different

01:02:57.220 --> 01:02:58.330
from another location.

01:02:58.330 --> 01:03:02.160
You are not able to
write that anymore.

01:03:02.160 --> 01:03:05.820
So uniformity is
another symmetry

01:03:05.820 --> 01:03:08.774
that I kind of implicitly used.

01:03:08.774 --> 01:03:10.526
Yes?

01:03:10.526 --> 01:03:12.570
AUDIENCE: When your
