01:03:45.380 --> 01:03:52.160
PROFESSOR: So again, once
I come to this stage,

01:03:52.160 --> 01:04:00.100
what it amounts to is
that I have constructed

01:04:00.100 --> 01:04:13.710
a kind of energy as a function
of a deformation field, which

01:04:13.710 --> 01:04:16.800
in the limit of very
long wavelengths

01:04:16.800 --> 01:04:21.535
has this very simple form
which is the integral du by dx

01:04:21.535 --> 01:04:22.035
squared.

01:04:24.620 --> 01:04:26.190
There are higher order terms.

01:04:26.190 --> 01:04:29.460
But hopefully in the
limit of long wavelengths,

01:04:29.460 --> 01:04:32.525
the higher derivatives
will disappear.

01:04:32.525 --> 01:04:35.050
In the limit of
small deformation,

01:04:35.050 --> 01:04:38.280
the higher order
terms will disappear.

01:04:38.280 --> 01:04:41.230
So the lowest order term
at long wavelengths,

01:04:41.230 --> 01:04:45.670
et cetera, is
parametrized by this 1k.

01:04:45.670 --> 01:04:51.110
If I fully transport it, I will
just get k over 2k squared.

01:04:51.110 --> 01:04:53.770
When I take the frequency
that corresponds to that,

01:04:53.770 --> 01:04:57.590
I will get that
kind of behavior.

01:04:57.590 --> 01:05:02.440
So by kind of relying on
these kinds of statements

01:05:02.440 --> 01:05:07.230
about symmetry, et cetera,
I was able to guess that.

01:05:07.230 --> 01:05:09.650
Now, let's go and do
with this for the case

01:05:09.650 --> 01:05:15.660
of material in three dimensions.

01:05:15.660 --> 01:05:18.800
Actually, in any dimensions,
in higher dimensions.

01:05:26.800 --> 01:05:31.120
So I take a solid
in three dimensions,

01:05:31.120 --> 01:05:34.190
or maybe a film in 2 dimensions.

01:05:34.190 --> 01:05:40.380
I can still describe
it's deformations

01:05:40.380 --> 01:05:46.320
at low enough temperature in
terms of long wavelength modes.

01:05:46.320 --> 01:05:47.940
I do the coarse graining.

01:05:47.940 --> 01:05:49.010
I have U of x.

01:05:49.010 --> 01:05:53.760
Actually, both U and
x are now vectors.

01:05:53.760 --> 01:05:57.310
And what I want to
do is to construct

01:05:57.310 --> 01:06:02.680
a potential that
corresponds to this end.

01:06:02.680 --> 01:06:05.200
OK?

01:06:05.200 --> 01:06:09.860
So I will use the
idea of locality.

01:06:09.860 --> 01:06:13.515
And I write it as an integral
over however many dimensions

01:06:13.515 --> 01:06:14.340
I have.

01:06:14.340 --> 01:06:17.880
So d is the
dimensionality of space

01:06:17.880 --> 01:06:22.620
of some kind of
an energy density.

01:06:22.620 --> 01:06:27.480
And the energy density now
will depend on U. Actually,

01:06:27.480 --> 01:06:32.250
U has many components,
U alpha of x.

01:06:32.250 --> 01:06:38.000
Derivatives of U-- so I will
have du alpha by dx beta.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:40.650
And you can see that
higher order derivatives,

01:06:40.650 --> 01:06:43.240
they're really more
and more indices.

01:06:43.240 --> 01:06:47.458
So the complication
now is that I

01:06:47.458 --> 01:06:49.270
have additional
indices involved.

01:06:52.120 --> 01:06:58.540
The symmetry that I will use
is a slightly more complicated

01:06:58.540 --> 01:07:01.080
version of what I had before.

01:07:01.080 --> 01:07:05.870
I will take the
crystal, U of x, and I

01:07:05.870 --> 01:07:10.895
can translate it
just as I did before.

01:07:10.895 --> 01:07:15.020
And I just say that this
translation of crystal

01:07:15.020 --> 01:07:17.894
does not change its energy.

01:07:17.894 --> 01:07:19.060
But you know something else?

01:07:19.060 --> 01:07:22.990
I can take my crystal,
and I can rotate it.

01:07:22.990 --> 01:07:25.660
The internal energy
should not change.

01:07:25.660 --> 01:07:32.730
So there is a rotation
of this that also you

01:07:32.730 --> 01:07:34.590
can put the c inside of.

01:07:34.590 --> 01:07:37.450
Before or after rotation,
it doesn't matter.

01:07:37.450 --> 01:07:43.050
The energy should
not depend on that.

01:07:43.050 --> 01:07:45.020
OK.

01:07:45.020 --> 01:07:48.660
So let's see what we
have to construct.

01:07:48.660 --> 01:07:50.080
I can write down the answer.

01:07:50.080 --> 01:07:55.720
So first of all, we know
immediately that the energy

01:07:55.720 --> 01:08:00.640
cannot depend on U itself for
the same reason as before.

01:08:00.640 --> 01:08:02.400
It can depend on derivatives.

01:08:02.400 --> 01:08:05.100
But this rotation
and derivatives

01:08:05.100 --> 01:08:07.140
is a little bit strange.

01:08:07.140 --> 01:08:11.200
So I'm going to use a trick.

01:08:11.200 --> 01:08:19.210
If I do this in Fourier
space, like I did over here,

01:08:19.210 --> 01:08:24.230
I went from this to
k over 2 integral dk

01:08:24.230 --> 01:08:28.600
k squared U tilde of k squared.

01:08:31.710 --> 01:08:35.260
If I stick with sufficiently
low derivatives,

01:08:35.260 --> 01:08:39.770
only at the level of the
second order derivatives,

01:08:39.770 --> 01:08:42.890
if I have a second order form
that depends on something

01:08:42.890 --> 01:08:47.160
like this, I can still
go to Fourier space.

01:08:47.160 --> 01:08:51.390
And the answer will be of
the form integral d dk.

01:08:51.390 --> 01:08:56.979
The different k modes will only
get coupled from higher order

01:08:56.979 --> 01:08:58.939
terms, third order
terms, et cetera.

01:08:58.939 --> 01:09:01.160
At the level of
quadratic, I know

01:09:01.160 --> 01:09:04.760
that the answer is
proportional to d dk.

01:09:04.760 --> 01:09:09.029
And for all of the reasons that
we have been discussing so far,

01:09:09.029 --> 01:09:13.640
the answer is going
to be U of k squared

01:09:13.640 --> 01:09:19.090
times some function of k, like
k squared, k to the fourth.

01:09:19.090 --> 01:09:24.300
Now, whatever I
put over here has

01:09:24.300 --> 01:09:28.300
to be invariant under rotations.

01:09:28.300 --> 01:09:31.029
So, let's see.

01:09:31.029 --> 01:09:34.590
I know that the answer
that I write here

01:09:34.590 --> 01:09:36.324
should be quadratic
[INAUDIBLE] tilde.

01:09:39.050 --> 01:09:41.920
It should be at
least quadratic in k,

01:09:41.920 --> 01:09:43.684
because I'm looking
at derivatives.

01:09:43.684 --> 01:09:47.510
In the same way
that I had k here,

01:09:47.510 --> 01:09:52.000
I should have factors of k here.

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:55.760
But k is a vector when I
go to three dimensions.

01:09:55.760 --> 01:09:59.590
U becomes a vector when
I go to three dimensions.

01:09:59.590 --> 01:10:03.120
So I want to construct
something that

01:10:03.120 --> 01:10:07.630
involves quadratic in vector
k, quadratic in vector U,

01:10:07.630 --> 01:10:09.830
and is also invariant
under rotations.

01:10:13.140 --> 01:10:16.340
One thing that I
know is that if I

01:10:16.340 --> 01:10:19.500
do a dot product of two
vectors, that dot product

01:10:19.500 --> 01:10:21.480
is invariant on the rotations.

01:10:21.480 --> 01:10:23.050
So I have two vectors.

01:10:23.050 --> 01:10:26.680
So I know, therefore,
that k squared,

01:10:26.680 --> 01:10:30.710
k dot k is a
rotational invariant.

01:10:30.710 --> 01:10:38.830
The tilde of k squared is
rotationally invariant.

01:10:38.830 --> 01:10:48.230
But also, k dot U
tilde of k squared

01:10:48.230 --> 01:10:51.230
is rotationally invariant.

01:10:51.230 --> 01:10:52.630
OK?

01:10:52.630 --> 01:10:57.290
So what I can do is I can say
that the most general form

01:10:57.290 --> 01:11:03.500
that I will write down
will allow 2 terms.

01:11:03.500 --> 01:11:07.830
The coefficients of that
are traditionally called mu.

01:11:07.830 --> 01:11:09.510
This is mu over 2.

01:11:09.510 --> 01:11:13.540
This one is called mu
plus lambda over 2.

01:11:13.540 --> 01:11:15.992
Actually, I have to put an
absolute value squared here.

01:11:21.080 --> 01:11:26.270
So that's the most
general theory

01:11:26.270 --> 01:11:31.330
of elasticity in any
number of dimensions

01:11:31.330 --> 01:11:38.060
that is consistent with this
symmetry that I have here.

01:11:38.060 --> 01:11:39.990
And it turns out
that this corresponds

01:11:39.990 --> 01:11:43.140
to elasticity of materials
that are isotropic.

01:11:51.240 --> 01:11:55.280
And they are described by
2 elastic coefficients,

01:11:55.280 --> 01:11:58.570
mu and lambda, that are called
[INAUDIBLE] coefficient.

01:11:58.570 --> 01:12:01.840
Mu is also related
to shear modules.

01:12:01.840 --> 01:12:07.000
Actually, mu and lambda combined
are related to [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:10.380
And if I want, in fact,
to fully transform

01:12:10.380 --> 01:12:17.190
this back to the space, in
real space the can be written

01:12:17.190 --> 01:12:24.500
as mu over 2 mu alpha
beta of x mu alpha

01:12:24.500 --> 01:12:29.170
beta over x, where the sum over
alpha and beta takes place.

01:12:29.170 --> 01:12:32.060
Alpha and beta run from 1 to d.

01:12:32.060 --> 01:12:34.710
And the other term,
lambda over 2,

01:12:34.710 --> 01:12:39.960
is U alpha alpha of
x, U beta beta of x.

01:12:39.960 --> 01:12:44.020
And this object, U
alpha beta, is one half

01:12:44.020 --> 01:12:51.395
of the symmeterized derivatives,
du alpha by dx beta plus du

01:12:51.395 --> 01:12:54.470
beta by dx alpha.

01:12:54.470 --> 01:12:59.436
And it's called the strength

01:12:59.436 --> 01:13:00.250
AUDIENCE: Question.

01:13:00.250 --> 01:13:02.340
PROFESSOR: Yes?

01:13:02.340 --> 01:13:05.360
AUDIENCE: So are
you still looking

01:13:05.360 --> 01:13:08.601
in the regime of low
energy expectations?

01:13:08.601 --> 01:13:09.226
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:13:09.226 --> 01:13:10.890
That's right.

01:13:10.890 --> 01:13:13.130
AUDIENCE: So wouldn't
the discreteness

01:13:13.130 --> 01:13:17.470
of the allowed wave
vectors become important?

01:13:17.470 --> 01:13:19.280
And if so, why are
you integrating

01:13:19.280 --> 01:13:20.580
rather than discrete summon?

01:13:23.340 --> 01:13:24.360
PROFESSOR: OK.

